\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec3 English Language Translations of the\'a0
\f2\i Tao Te Ching
\f3\i0\b0\fs24 \strokec3 \
\'a0\
"The thirty spokes unite in the one nave; but it is on the empty space for the axle, that the use of the wheel depends.\uc0\u8232 Clay is fashioned into vessels; but it is on their empty hollowness, that their use depends.\u8232 The door and windows are cut out from the walls to form an apartment; but it is on the empty space within, that its use depends.\'a0\u8232 Therefore, what has a positive existence serves for profitable adaptation, and what has not that for actual usefulness."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 James Legge}}, 1891, Chapter 11\'a0 \'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes unite in one nave and on that which is non-existent on the hole in the nave depends the wheel's utility.\uc0\u8232 Clay is molded into a vessel and on that which is non-existent on its hollowness depends the vessel's utility.\u8232 By cutting out doors and windows we build a house and on that which is non-existent on the empty space within depends the house's utility.\'a0\u8232 Therefore, existence renders actual but non-existence renders useful."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 D. T. Suzuki and Paul Carus}}, 1913, Chapter 11\'a0\'a0 \'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes share the hub of a wheel;\uc0\u8232 yet it is its center that makes it useful.\u8232 You can mould clay into a vessel;\u8232 yet, it is its emptiness that makes it useful.\u8232 Cut doors and windows from the walls of a house;\u8232 but the ultimate use of the house\u8232 will depend on that part where nothing exists.\u8232 Therefore, something is shaped into what is;\u8232 but its usefulness comes from what is not."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Kari Hohne}}, 2009, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec3 "We fire clay to make a cup,\uc0\u8232 But we use the empty space in the center\u8232 We build walls to make a room,\u8232 But we use the empty space they surround\u8232 We form a wheel to spin,\u8232 But we need the axle hole to use it\u8232 The point:\u8232 Having something is good only to the extent\u8232 That it makes nothingness usable"\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Ted Wrigley}}, Chapter 11\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec3 "The Nature of Usefulness ...\uc0\u8232 Thirty spokes will converge\u8232 In the hub of a wheel;\u8232 But the use of the cart\u8232 Will depend on the part\u8232 Of the hub that is void.\u8232 With a wall all around\u8232 A clay bowl is molded;\u8232 But the use of the bowl\u8232 Will depend on the part\u8232 Of the bowl that is void.\u8232 Cut out windows and doors\u8232 In the house as you build;\u8232 But the use of the house\u8232 Will depend on the space\u8232 In the walls that is void.\u8232 So advantage is had\u8232 From whatever is there;\u8232 But usefulness rises\u8232 From whatever is not."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Raymond Blakney}}, 1955, Chapter 11
\f6 \strokec3 \
\'a0\
\'a0\

\f3 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes join at a hub: their use for the cart is where they are not.\uc0\u8232 When the potter's wheel makes a pot, the use of the pot is precisely where there is nothing.\u8232 When you open the doors and windows for a room, it is where there is nothing that they are useful to the room.\u8232 Therefore being is for benefit, nonbeing is for usefulness."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Thomas Cleary}}, 1991, Chapter 11
\f6 \strokec3 \
\'a0\
\'a0\

\f3 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes unite in the middle of the wheel,\uc0\u8232 And because of the part between them where nothing exists,\u8232 We enjoy the use of the carriage wheel.\u8232 Clay is formed into bowls and vessels,\u8232 And because of the hollow in it where nothing exists,\u8232 We use them as vessels.\u8232 Doors and windows are cut into the walls of the house,\u8232 And since they are empty space, we can use them.\u8232 Therefore, on the one hand, we have the advantage of what exists,\u8232 And, on the other, we utilize the non-existent.\u8232 Without that which does not exist, we cannot take advantage of the wheel, the vessel, or the house.\u8232 Without wooden spokes, clay, and walls, we cannot take advantage of the space they contain.\u8232 Ultimately, existence and non-existence coexist and are intertwined."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Chohan Chou-Wing}}, Chapter 11
\f6 \strokec3 \
\'a0\
\'a0\

\f3 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes are joined around the wheel's hub,\uc0\u8232 Its non-being makes the carriage useful.\u8232 Clay is molded to make a pot,\u8232 Its non-being provides the utility.\u8232 Doors and windows are cut to make a room,\u8232 Their utility is furnished by non-being.\u8232 Therefore,\u8232 Being only facilitates, non-being provides utility."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 David Hong Cheng}}, 2000, Chapter 11
\f6 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes share the wheel's hub;\
It is the center hole that makes it useful.\
Shape clay into a vessel;\
It is the space within that makes it useful.\
Cut doors and windows for a room;\
It is the holes which make it useful.\
Therefore benefit comes from what is there;\
Usefulness from what is not there."\
-\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Gia-fu Feng and Jane English}}, 1989, Chapter 11\'a0\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes surround one nave, the usefulness of the wheel is always in that empty innermost.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 You fashion clay to make a bowl, the usefulness of the bowl is always in that empty innermost.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 You cut out doors and windows to make a house, their usefulness to a house is always in their empty space.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore profit comes from external form, but usefulness comes from the empty innermost."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Isabella Mears}}, 1916, Chapter 11\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes unite in one nave, and by that part which is non-existent\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 (i.e. the hole in the center of it), it is useful for a carriage wheel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Earth is molded into vessels, and by their hollowness\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 they are useful as vessels.\'a0\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Doors and windows are cut out in order to make a house,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 and by its hollowness it is useful as a house.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 So then existence may be said to correspond to gain,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but non-existence to use."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 John Chalmers}}, 1968, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes unite in the wheel's hub;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is precisely where there is nothing,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 that makes the wheel so useful.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We shape and fire clay into a vessel;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is precisely the space within that makes the clay pots so useful.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We chisel out the doors and windows for a room;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is precisely in these empty spaces that makes the room so useful.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore benefit comes from what is there;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Usefulness comes from what is not there."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Bram den Hond}}, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Fit thirty spokes into the hub of a wheel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is the space between the spokes that makes the wheel valuable; thus the vehicle can be put to use.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Bake clay and make it into cups.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is the space within the cup that makes it valuable; thus the cup is useful.\'a0\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Cut out doors and windows.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is the space created by the doors and windows which makes them valuable; thus a house is useful.\'a0\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore, what has substance is beneficial.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 What is without substance is useful."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Nina Correa}}, 2005, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"We join spokes together in a hub,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but it is the center hole that provides the utility of the wheel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We form clay into a container,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but it is the emptiness inside\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 that holds whatever we want.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We build walls for a house,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But it is the empty space inside\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 that we live in.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore: we work with being,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But it is in non-being that there is true usefulness."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 John Dicus}}, 2002, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "We put thirty spokes together and call it a wheel;\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 But it is on the space where there is nothing\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 That the usefulness of the wheel depends.\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 We turn clay to make a vessel;\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 But it is on the space where there is nothing\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 That the usefulness of the vessel depends.\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 We pierce doors and windows to make a house;\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 And it is on these spaces where there is nothing\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 That the usefulness of the house depends.\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 Therefore just as we take advantage of what is,\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 We should recognize the usefulness of what is not."\cb1 \strokec3 \
\cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Arthur Waley}}, 1934, Chapter 11\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

