san shih fu kung yi ku.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 tang ch'i wu, yu ch'\'ea chih yung.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 yen ch'ih yi wei ch'i.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 tang ch'i wu yu ch'i chih yung.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 tso hu yu yi wei shih.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 tang ch'i wu, yu shih chih yung.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 ku yu chih yi wei li.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 wu chih yi wei yung.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Wade-Giles Romanization,\'a0
\f4\i \cb2 \strokec3 Tao Te Ching
\f3\i0 \cb2 \strokec3 , Chapter 11\'a0\'a0\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "The thirty spokes of a carriage wheel uniting at the nave are made useful by the hole in the centre, where nothing exists.\
Vessels of moulded earth are useful by reason of their hollowness.\
Doors and windows are useful by being cut out.\
A house is useful because of its emptiness.\
Existence, therefore, is like unto gain, but Non-Existence to use."\
-\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Walter Gorn Old}}, 1904, Chapter 11\'a0\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes unite around the nave;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 From their not-being (loss of their individuality)\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Arises the utility of the wheel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Mold clay into a vessel;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 From its not-being (in the vessel's hollow)\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Arises the utility of the vessel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Cut out doors and windows in the house (-wall),\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 From their not-being (empty space) arises the utility of the house.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore by the existence of things we profit.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 And by the non-existence of things we are served."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Lin Yutang}}, 1955, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes share one hub,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 yet the spokes and the hub cannot make use of the carriage.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Mix water, mud and earth and they can be shaped into a vessel,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 yet they cannot make use of the vessel itself.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Cut out windows and doors to create a room,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 yet they cannot make use of the room itself.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore take the useful as the useless, the useless as the useful."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Chao-Hsiu Chen}}, 2004, Chapter 11\'a0\
\'a0\
