"Thirty spokes are joined together in a wheel,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but it is the center hole\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 that allows the wheel to function.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We mold clay into a pot,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but it is the emptiness inside\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 that makes the vessel useful.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We fashion wood for a house,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but it is the emptiness inside\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 that makes it livable.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We work with the substantial,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 but the emptiness is what we use."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 John H. McDonald}}, 1996, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "We fire clay to make a cup,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But we use the empty space in the center\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We build walls to make a room,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But we use the empty space they surround\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We form a wheel to spin,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But we need the axle hole to use it\
The point:\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Having something is good only to the extent\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 That it makes nothingness usable.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Ted Wrigley}}, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Though thirty spokes may be joined in one hub, the utility of the carriage lies in what is not there.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Though clay may be moulded into a vase, the utility of the vase lies in what is not there\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Though doors and windows may be cut to make a house, the utility of the house lies in what is not there.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Therefore, taking advantage of what is, we recognize the utility of what is not."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Jan J. L. Duyvendak}}, 1954, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes share a hub;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 The usefulness of the cart\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 lies in the space where there is nothing.\
Clay is kneaded into a vessel;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 The usefulness of the vessel\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 lies in the space where there is nothing.\
A room is created by cutting out doors and windows;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 The usefulness of the room\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 \'a0 lies in the space where there is nothing.\
Therefore,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 The benefit of things lies in the usefulness of nothing."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Yasuhiko Genku Kimura}}, 2004, Chapter 11\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 \'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes meet in one hub, but the need for the cart existed when as yet it was not.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Clay is fashioned into vessels, but the need for the vessel existed when as yet it was not.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Doors and windows are cut out to make a house, but the need for the house existed when as yet it was not.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Hence there is a profitableness in that which is and a need in that which is not."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 C. Spurgeon Medhurst}}, 1905, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes will converge\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 In the hub of a wheel;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But the use of the cart\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Will depend on the part\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Of the hub that is void.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 With a wall all around\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 A clay bowl is molded;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But the use of the bowl\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Will depend on the part\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Of the bowl that is void.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Cut out windows and doors\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 In the house as you build;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But the use of the house\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Will depend on the space\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 In the walls that is void.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 So advantage is had\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 From whatever is there;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But usefulness rises\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 From whatever is not."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Raymond Blackney}}, 1955, Chapter 11\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes unite in one hub: on what in it is nothing\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 depends the usefulness of the cart.\
Clay may be made into vessels: on what in them is nothing\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 depends the usefulness of the vessels.\
We cut out doors and windows to make a house: on what in them\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 is nothing depends the usefulness of the house.\
So the existent may be regarded as profitable; the non-existent\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 may be regarded as useful. The sage discards the outer life in favour of the inner."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 P. J. Maclagan}}, 1898, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty Spokes converge upon a single hub;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is on the hole in the center that the use of the cart hinges.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We make a bowl or cup from a lump of clay;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is the empty space within the vessel that makes it useful.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 We make doors and windows for a room;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is the empty spaces that make the room livable.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Thus, take advantage of what is visible, by making use of what is not visible."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 J. L. Trottier}}, 1994, Chapter 11\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Although the wheel has thirty spokes its utility lies in the emptiness of the hub.\
The jar is made by kneading clay, but its usefulness consists in its capacity.\
A room is made by cutting out windows and doors through the walls, but the space the walls contain measures the room's value.\
In the same way matter is necessary to form, but the value of reality lies in its immateriality.\
Or thus: a material body is necessary to existence, but the value of a life is measured by its immaterial soul."\
-\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Dwight Goddard and Henri Borel}}, 1919, Chapter 11\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb1 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes, uniting in a nave, were employed in olden times before the invention of carriages.\uc0\u8232 Clay made into utensils was employed before the time of palaces and dwellings when there were no sacrificial vases, goblets, or bowls.\u8232 A door and a window, hewn in a hill-side, did duty for a residence before the erection of houses.\u8232 Wherefore, the possession of these things may be regarded as beneficial,\u8232 while their former absence may be said to have been useful in that it led to the necessity of their being made."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Frederic Henry Balfour}}, 1884, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa0\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec3 "Drei\'dfig Speichen umgeben eine Nabe:\uc0\u8232 In ihrem Nichts besteht des Wagens Werk.\u8232 Man h\'f6hlet Ton und bildet ihn zu T\'f6pfen:\u8232 In ihrem Nichts besteht des T\'f6pfe Werk.\u8232 Man gr\'e4bt T\'fcren und Fenster, damit die Kammer werde:\u8232 In ihrem Nichts besteht der Kammer Werk.\u8232 Darum: Was ist, dient zum Besitz.\u8232 Was nicht ist, dient zum Werk."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Richard Wilhelm,}}\'a01911, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Die Wirksamkeit des Unsichtbaren im Sichtbaren\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Drei\'dfig Speichen enden in einer Nabe;\u8232 doch erst das Loch in der Nabe\u8232 wirkt des Rades Brauchbarkeit.\u8232 \u8232 Ton knetend bildet man Gef\'e4\'dfe;\u8232 doch erst ihr Hohlraum gibt ihnen Brauchbarkeit.\u8232 \u8232 Mauern, von Fenstern und T\'fcren durchbrochen, bilden R\'e4ume;\u8232 doch erst die Leere des Raums gibt ihnen Brauchbarkeit.\u8232 \u8232 So gibt das Stoffliche zwar Eignung,\u8232 das Unstoffliche aber erst den Wert."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Rudolf Backofen}}, 1949, Chapter 11\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec3 \'a0\
\'a0\
"The empty hub at center\uc0\u8232 Allows a wheel to roll\u8232 The vacancy within defines\u8232 The function of a bowl
\f6 \strokec3 \

\f3 \strokec3 The openness within a house\uc0\u8232 Provides location to reside\u8232 The open space that is my heart\u8232 Is where ten thousand things abide."\u8232 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Jim Clatfelder}}, 2000, Chapter 11
\f6 \strokec3 \

\f3 \strokec3 \'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes share one hub.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Adapt the nothing therein to the purpose in hand, and you will have the use of the cart.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Knead clay in order to make a vessel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Adapt the nothing therein to the purpose in hand, and you will have the use of the vessel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Cut out doors and windows in order to make a room.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Adapt the nothing therein to the purpose in hand, and you will have the use of the room.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Thus what we gain is Something, yet it is by virtue of Nothing that this can be put to use."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 D. C. Lau}}, 1963, Chapter 11\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Thirty spokes share one hub.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is just the space (the Nothingness) between them\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 That makes a cart function as a cart.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Knead clay to make a vessel\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 And you find within it the space\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 That makes a vessel as a vessel.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 To build a house with doors and windows\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 And you find within them the space\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 That makes a house function as a house.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Hence the Being (substance) can provide a condition\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Under which usefulness is found,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 But the Nothingness (space) is the usefulness itself."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Gu Zengkun}}, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes are made one by holes in a hub,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 By vacancies joining them for a wheel's use;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 The use of clay in moulding pitchers\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Comes from the hollow of its absence;\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Doors, windows, in a house,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Are used for their emptiness:\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Thus we are helped by what is not\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 To use what is."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Witter Bynner}}, 1944, Chapter 11\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa0\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 "Thirty spokes unite in a nave, but the nothingness in the hub\
Gives to the wheel its usefulness, for thereupon it goes round;\
The potter kneads the clay as he works, with many a twist and rub,\
But in the nothingness within, the vessel's use is found;\
Doors and windows cut in the walls thereby a room will make,\
But in its nothingness is found the room' s utility;\
So the profit of existences is only for the sake\
Of non-existences, where all the use is found to be."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Isaac Winter Heysinger}}, 1903, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"A wheel is made of thirty perceptible spokes, but it turns due to the imperceptible central axis of the hub.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Vessels are made of perceptible clay, but it is their imperceptible hollow that is useful.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 The imperceptible holes which make the doors and windows of a house, are its essentials.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 It is the imperceptible that produces effects and results."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Derek Bryce}}, 1999, Chapter 11\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\
"Trente rais se r\'e9unissent autour d'un moyeu.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 C'est de son vide que d\'e9pend l'usage du char.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 On p\'e9trit de la terre glaise pour faire des vases.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 C'est de son vide que d\'e9pend l'usage des vases.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 On perce des portes et des fen\'eatres pour faire une maison.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 C'est de leur vide que d\'e9pend l'usage de la maison.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 C'est pourquoi l'utilit\'e9 vient de l'\'eatre, l'usage na\'eet du non-\'eatre."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translated by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/ttclztrans3.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Stanislas Julien}}, 1842, Chapter 11\
\
"Treinta radios convergen en el centro de una rueda,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 pero es su vac\'edo\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 lo que hace \'fatil al carro.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Se moldea la arcilla para hacer la vasija,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 pero de su vac\'edo\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 depende el uso de la vasija.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 Se abren puertas y ventanas\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 en los muros de una casa,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 y es el vac\'edo\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 lo que permite habitarla.\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 En el Ser centramos nuestro inter\'e9s,\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 pero del No-Ser depende la utilidad."\cb1 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 \cb2 \strokec3 -\'a0 Translation from\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.egreenway.com/taoism/spanish.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb2 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Wiki Source}}, 2013,\'a0
